Sure, I can help you with that! Creating themes with different color values using Sass and Bootstrap 5.3's color modes is a great way to customize your site's appearance. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to proceed:

    Install Bootstrap 5.3 and Sass:
    Make sure you have Bootstrap 5.3 and Sass installed in your project. You can install them via npm using the following commands:
    
    npm install bootstrap@5.3.0
npm install sass

bash

npm install bootstrap@5.3.0
npm install sass

    Set up your project structure:
    Create a folder structure for your Sass files. For example:

markdown

- src
  - sass
    - themes
      - _theme-default.scss
      - _theme-blue.scss
      - _theme-green.scss
    - main.scss

    Create your default color variables:
    In the _theme-default.scss file, define your default color variables that will be used if no specific theme is applied. For example:

scss

// src/sass/themes/_theme-default.scss

// Your default color variables
$primary: #007bff;
$secondary: #6c757d;
// Add other color variables as needed

    Create your theme files:
    In the _theme-blue.scss and _theme-green.scss files (or as many themes as you want), define the specific color values for each theme:

scss

// src/sass/themes/_theme-blue.scss

// Theme-specific color variables
$primary: #0d6efd;
$secondary: #6c757d;
// Add other color variables as needed

scss

// src/sass/themes/_theme-green.scss

// Theme-specific color variables
$primary: #198754;
$secondary: #6c757d;
// Add other color variables as needed

    Create the main.scss file:
    In the main.scss file, import the Bootstrap 5.3 Sass source and then import your default theme:

scss

// src/sass/main.scss

// Import Bootstrap 5.3 Sass source
@import 'node_modules/bootstrap/scss/bootstrap';

// Import your default theme
@import 'themes/theme-default';

// More custom styles can go here...

    Compile Sass with Webpack:
    Configure Webpack to compile your Sass files. You'll need to set up a rule for .scss files and use sass-loader to process them.

For example, your webpack.config.js might look like this:

js

const path = require('path');

module.exports = {
  entry: './src/sass/main.scss',
  output: {
    filename: 'styles.css',
    path: path.resolve(__dirname, 'dist'),
  },
  module: {
    rules: [
      {
        test: /\.scss$/,
        use: [
          'style-loader', // or MiniCssExtractPlugin.loader to create a separate CSS file
          'css-loader',
          'sass-loader',
        ],
      },
    ],
  },
};

    Apply themes in your HTML:
    Now, in your HTML file, include the compiled styles.css file:

html

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>My Themed Website</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="dist/styles.css">
</head>
<body>
  <!-- Your content goes here -->
</body>
</html>

    Change the theme dynamically:
    To change the theme dynamically, you'll need to use JavaScript to change the CSS variable values for your themes.

For example, if you want to change to the blue theme, you can use the following JavaScript code:

js

// JavaScript to change theme dynamically
const changeToBlueTheme = () => {
  document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--primary-color', '#0d6efd');
  document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--secondary-color', '#6c757d');
  // Add other color variables as needed
};

// Call this function to apply the blue theme
changeToBlueTheme();

Remember to update your CSS variable names to match the ones you define in your theme files.

That's it! Now you have a setup to create multiple themes for your site using Bootstrap 5.3's color modes. You can create additional theme files for different color variations and use JavaScript to switch between them dynamically.

The issue you are facing with the Bootstrap 5 tooltip and collapse not working as expected may be due to the way you are initializing the Bootstrap components in a Vue 3 project. Bootstrap's JavaScript components are jQuery-based, and it might cause conflicts when used with Vue 3.

To resolve the issue, you can use a library like `bootstrap.native` or `bs5-vue` to handle Bootstrap components without jQuery and ensure compatibility with Vue 3.

Here's how you can modify your project to use `bs5-vue`:

1. Install `bs5-vue`:

```bash
npm install bs5-vue
```

2. In your `main.ts` or `main.js` file, import the `bs5-vue` library and initialize it:

```javascript
import { createApp } from 'vue';
import App from './App.vue';
import bs5 from 'bs5-vue';

const app = createApp(App);
app.use(bs5);
app.mount('#app');
```

3. In your Vue components, you can now use Bootstrap 5 components without conflicts:

```vue
<template>
  <div>
    <h1>This is homepage</h1>
    <i
      class="fas fa-info-circle"
      data-bs-toggle="tooltip"
      data-bs-placement="top"
      title="Tooltip on top"
      ref="info"
    >
      Check
    </i>
  </div>
</template>

<script setup>
import { ref, onMounted } from 'vue';

const info = ref(null);
let infoTooltip;

onMounted(() => {
  infoTooltip = new Tooltip(info.value);
});
</script>
```

Similarly, you can apply the same approach to your components using the Bootstrap 5 collapse.

By using `bs5-vue`, you can ensure that Bootstrap 5 components work smoothly with Vue 3, and it should resolve the issue of the tooltip and collapse not functioning correctly in your project.

