OK so NtOS can be considered as a separate theme on top of Bootstrap Light and Bootstrap Dark.
The idea here is to follow https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/customize/color-modes/#custom-color-modes that you can define apparently within your `_ntos.scss` included as you've done it with `@import "ntos";`.

In this file it's possible to modify the values of the CSS vars that are provided by the framework. For example:

```scss
[data-bs-theme="ntos"] {
  --bs-body-color: var(--bs-white);
  --bs-body-color-rgb: #{to-rgb($white)};
  --bs-body-bg: var(--bs-blue);
  --bs-body-bg-rgb: #{to-rgb($blue)};
  --bs-tertiary-bg: #{$blue-600};

  .dropdown-menu {
    --bs-dropdown-bg: #{mix($blue-500, $blue-600)};
    --bs-dropdown-link-active-bg: #{$blue-700};
  }

  .btn-secondary {
    --bs-btn-bg: #{mix($gray-600, $blue-400, .5)};
    --bs-btn-border-color: #{rgba($white, .25)};
    --bs-btn-hover-bg: #{darken(mix($gray-600, $blue-400, .5), 5%)};
    --bs-btn-hover-border-color: #{rgba($white, .25)};
    --bs-btn-active-bg: #{darken(mix($gray-600, $blue-400, .5), 10%)};
    --bs-btn-active-border-color: #{rgba($white, .5)};
    --bs-btn-focus-border-color: #{rgba($white, .5)};
    --bs-btn-focus-box-shadow: 0 0 0 .25rem rgba(255, 255, 255, .2);
  }
}
```

But here, we are still using Bootstrap color palette. In your case, you'll probably want a different color palette, maybe some intermediate tokens like semantic tokens and so on.
You can then create all the Sass variables you want (or CSS variables) to handle that. For example:

```scss
[data-bs-theme="ntos"] {
  $primary: #4c0bce;

  /* ... */

  .btn-secondary {
    --bs-btn-bg: #{$primary}; // And your secondary button background color will be violet
    /* ... */
  }
}
```

This is basically what we are doing to handle the dark mode:
- Our [_root.scss](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/main/scss/_root.scss) at then end of the file will redefine CSS vars
- Our [_variables-dark.scss](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/main/scss/_variables-dark.scss) will define some specific Sass variables to be able to switch dynamically the content of the CSS vars
- There is more complexity with the maps within the framework we want to simplify in v6 with the `$theme-colors-*` but I think you can avoid this part to handle your own maps and override the CSS in your own way
- In some components in the framework, we need to do stuff like this too to override only a specific part (here to handle icons with CSS variables):

```css
@if $enable-dark-mode {
  @include color-mode(dark) {
    .accordion-button::after {
      --#{$prefix}accordion-btn-icon: #{escape-svg($accordion-button-icon-dark)};
      --#{$prefix}accordion-btn-active-icon: #{escape-svg($accordion-button-active-icon-dark)};
    }
  }
}
```

I think that's it.

There are several ways to organize your theme in terms of Sass and CSS properties.

I've never done the exercise to create a full theme that must work in cohabitation with the Bootstrap one, so maybe some information won't be too exact but I hope it can lead you to the right solution :)

@julien-deramond  I got it working. Had to use another `crate` `js_sys` so I can lookup for `js` symbols/stuff and call it from inside `rust` code.

For anyone in future having a similar problem, you need to call this function inside a `use_effect` hook where you render the `Toast`,
```rust
use js_sys::Reflect;
use wasm_bindgen::{prelude::Closure, JsCast, JsValue};
use web_sys::{window, Element, MouseEvent};

pub fn show_toast() {
    let window = window().expect("Error! Failed to get window");
    let document = window.document().expect("Error! Failed to get document");

    let toast_trigger = document
        .get_element_by_id("liveToastBtn")
        .expect("Error! Failed to get element by id liveToastBtn");
    let toast_live = document
        .get_element_by_id("liveToast")
        .expect("Error! Failed to get element by id liveToast");

    if !toast_trigger.is_undefined() {
        let bootstrap = Reflect::get(&window, &JsValue::from("bootstrap"))
            .expect("Error! Failed to get property bootstrap");
        let toast = Reflect::get(&bootstrap, &JsValue::from("Toast"))
            .expect("Error! Failed to get property Toast");
        let get_or_create_instance = Reflect::get(&toast, &JsValue::from("getOrCreateInstance"))
            .expect("Error! Failed to get property gerOrCreateInstance");

        let toast_bootstrap = get_or_create_instance
            .clone()
            .unchecked_into::<js_sys::Function>()
            .call1(&toast, &JsValue::from(toast_live))
            .expect("Error! Failed to call function getOrCreateInstance");

        let show_toast = Reflect::get(&toast_bootstrap, &JsValue::from("show"))
            .expect("Error! Failed to get property show");

        let callback = Closure::wrap(Box::new(move |_: MouseEvent| {
            show_toast
                .clone()
                .unchecked_into::<js_sys::Function>()
                .call0(&toast_bootstrap)
                .expect("Error! Failed to call function show");
        }) as Box<dyn FnMut(_)>);

        toast_trigger
            .unchecked_into::<Element>()
            .add_event_listener_with_callback("click", callback.as_ref().unchecked_ref())
            .expect("Error! Failed to add event listener");

        callback.forget();
    }
}
```

