Funny that your request urged me to to isolate the issue and, as a result, find a solution 😁

Here's the [StackBlitz](https://stackblitz.com/github/3baaady07/modal-typescript) solution.

Initially, I had the following code to handle varying modal content.
```ts
interface HTMLElementEventMap
{
   ["show.bs.modal"]: MouseEvent
}

modal.addEventListener("show.bs.modal", (e: HTMLElementEventMap["show.bs.modal"]) => {
   const invoker = e.relatedTarget as HTMLButtonElement // <-- didn't work
   // rest of the code ...
})
```
It turns out, I didn't need to enforce a type on the `e` argument as it is, by default, an `Event` type. Then within the handler block, `e` should be "type-casted" _(is that a word?)_ to `MouseEvent`.

The fix is...
```ts
modal.addEventListener("show.bs.modal", (e) => {
   const event = e as MouseEvent;
   const invoker = event.relatedTarget as HTMLButtonElement
   // rest of the code ...
})
```

Anyways, it's solved now.

