I've looked into the issue briefly, and although my solution may not be the cleanest, it should point you in the right direction.

In Bootstrap v4 (but no longer in v5), there were specific print-related styles that affected tables, which you can find in [this section of the Bootstrap v4 CSS](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/fa4fbc8798e432b37d6734e66c08da3985a75c89/dist/css/bootstrap.css#L10257-L10331).

What’s particularly relevant in your case is:
```css
@media print {
  .table td,
  .table th {
    background-color: #fff !important;
  }
}
```

This rule is the reason why, when you print your table, the cells default to a white background, even overriding Bootstrap’s standard gray background. That’s why your background color isn’t showing.

To help, I’ve put together [a CodePen](https://codepen.io/julien-deramond/pen/QWXoEew) based on your example. I didn’t delve into every detail, but I did manage to get a red background to appear when printing via Firefox (you'll need to trigger the print dialog to see it).

Here’s how I addressed it:

In the `<style>` block, I added:

```css
td.red-background {
  background-color: red !important;
}
```

The key here is using `!important` to override the Bootstrap default styles.

Then, I replaced your jQuery line:

```diff
- $(win.document.body).find('span.score_red').parent().css('background-color', 'red');
+ $(win.document.body).find('span.score_red').parent().addClass('red-background');
```

When using `.css('background-color', 'red');`, I think the `!important` is not applied, so Bootstrap's print-specific styles are still taking precedence. By switching to a class with a background color defined using `!important`, you can successfully override those styles.

Depending on your use case, you could simplify this further, perhaps by handling everything with a single class. 

Hope it can help :)

---

There is another alternative but needing to use Sass. In Bootstrap v4, if you customize your build to use Sass and set `$enable-print-styles` to `false` (see https://getbootstrap.com/docs/4.6/getting-started/theming/#sass-options), you wouldn't have this overridden print style done by Bootstrap v4.

You can clearly see that all the `@media print` code from Bootstrap is surrounded by `$enable-print-styles` here: https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/v4-dev/scss/_print.scss

Here's a link that explain how you can import Bootstrap in Sass in your project: https://getbootstrap.com/docs/4.6/getting-started/theming/#importing

