There’s a misunderstanding of how Sass variables work in general (not only with Bootstrap).

When you define Sass variables like `$primary`, `$secondary`, or `$blue` inside a CSS selector or pseudo-selector like `[data-bs-theme="custom"]`, these variables are locally scoped. This means they won't be available outside those `{ }`. 

This works because $primary is defined locally but at the same place
```scss
// SCSS
selectorA {
    $primary: #ff69b4;
    color: $primary;
}
```
This works too because $primary is defined globally and is available everywhere
```scss
// SCSS
$primary: #ff69b4;
selectorA {
    color: $primary;
}
```
This doesn’t work because $primary is not defined in the scope (inside the same `{ }`) nor globally.
```scss
// SCSS
selectorA {
    $primary: #ff69b4;
    color: $primary;
}
selectorB {
    background-color: $primary;
}
```
And this doesn’t work for the same reason.
```scss
// SCSS
selectorA {
    $primary: #ff69b4;
    color: $primary;
}
selectorA {
    background-color: $primary;
}
```
Both return
```
@error:7 Undefined variable.
  ╷
7 │     background-color: $primary;
  │                       ^^^^^^^^
  ╵
```

This is **different** from CSS custom properties (“variables”) because they are set to any **element** that matches the selector so this works:
```css
/* CSS */
selectorA {
    --primary: #ff69b4;
    color: var(--primary);
}
selectorA {
    background-color: var(--primary);
}

/* and even this works if selectorB selects the same element as selectorA */
selectorB {
    background-color: var(--primary);
}
```
CSS is applied to elements at runtime. Sass is compiled before, without any knowledge of elements in the so even in the case of the same selector it just doesn’t “connect the dots”.

You can [check the example in Sass playground](https://sass-lang.com/playground/#eJwzNCxOzUlNLskvclSo5lJQUCkoysxNLKq0UihKTbEGCiTn5+QXWcHFrblqubhQtSQlJmenF+WX5qXoYioGAOo/H9o=).

So you can’t just define `data-bs-theme="custom"] { sass variables here }` and call it a day as they are available only inside that part of your code.

[How to actually create a theme is described in the documentation](https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/customize/color-modes/#custom-color-modes).

Check the code in [`scss/_root.scss`](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/ec96eacd0e6f297a64ee058b22ce9f567c0860e3/scss/_root.scss#L132C1-L187C2), [`scss/_variables-dark.scss`](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/main/scss/_variables-dark.scss) and [`scss/_maps.scss`](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/ec96eacd0e6f297a64ee058b22ce9f567c0860e3/scss/_maps.scss#L52-L91) that is used to create the built-in dark theme. Also check where these files are used in [`scss/bootstrap.scss`](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/ec96eacd0e6f297a64ee058b22ce9f567c0860e3/scss/bootstrap.scss)

