```
Added it to the map:

```
$spacers: spacers-map($responsiveSpacers);
$negative-spacers: spacers-map($responsiveSpacers, true);
```

Custom function for map generating:

```
@function spacers-map($map, $negative: false) {
  $keys: ();
  $suffix: '';

  @if $negative == true {
    $suffix: 'n';
  }

  @each $breakpoint, $map in $responsiveSpacers {
    @each $key, $value in $map {
      $keys: map-merge(
        $keys,
        (#{$suffix}#{$key}: var(--#{$variable-prefix}spacer-#{$suffix}#{$key}))
      );
    }
  }

  @return $keys;
}
```

Root add:

```
:root {
  @each $breakpoint, $map in $responsiveSpacers {
    @include media-breakpoint-up($breakpoint) {
      @each $key, $value in $map {
        --#{$variable-prefix}spacer-#{$key}: #{$value};
      }

      @each $key, $value in negativify-map($map) {
        --#{$variable-prefix}spacer-#{$key}: #{$value};
      }
    }
  }
}

```

Hello @MartinKosicky 
Bootstrap's responsive grid system is based on CSS media queries, which use the viewport width (in this case, innerWidth) to determine the applicable breakpoint classes.
Your device's viewport width in both orientations exceeds the lg breakpoint (992px). Bootstrap breakpoints apply the largest matching class, so as long as your viewport width is above 992px, the lg rules will apply, regardless of whether you're in portrait or landscape (see https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/layout/grid/#grid-options).

If you want a specific rendering for this device, you could adjust by having orientation media queries (for portrait or landscape):

```css
@media (orientation: landscape) {
  .my-class {
    /* Custom styles for landscape mode */
  }
}
@media (orientation: portrait) {
  .my-class {
    /* Custom styles for portrait mode */
  }
}
```

or add custom breakpoints, something like:

```css
@media (max-width: 1002px) {
  .my-class {
    /* Override styles for narrow landscape widths */
  }
}
```

